  "text": "Apache Kafka enforces log retention policy through a comprehensive set of Java and Scala source files. The core retention enforcement is implemented in UnifiedLog.java (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/UnifiedLog.java), which contains the primary deletion methods: deleteOldSegments() serves as the main orchestration method that invokes three specific retention breach handlers.\n\nFor time-based retention enforcement, the deleteRetentionMsBreachedSegments() method checks if segments exceed the configured retention time (log.retention.ms). It compares the current timestamp against segment timestamps and removes segments that exceed the retentionMs threshold, using the segment's largestTimestamp() or last modified time.\n\nFor size-based retention enforcement, the deleteRetentionSizeBreachedSegments() method enforces the log.retention.bytes policy by calculating the total log size and removing segments when the log exceeds the configured retention size limit. It tracks the remaining bytes to delete using an AtomicLong diff variable.\n\nThe local retention helpers (localRetentionMs and localRetentionSize) determine whether to use local retention values or global values based on remote storage configuration. When remote storage is enabled and remote copy is enabled, local retention values are used; otherwise, the global retention values apply.\n\nConfiguration validation for retention policies is centralized in LogConfig.java (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/storage/internals/log/LogConfig.java). The validateRemoteStorageRetentionTime() method validates that log.retention.ms and local.retention.ms are properly configured, ensuring local retention does not exceed global retention. Similarly, validateRemoteStorageRetentionSize() validates that log.retention.bytes and local.retention.bytes follow the same constraint. The validateRetentionConfigsWhenRemoteCopyDisabled() method enforces that when remote copy is disabled, local retention must equal global retention.\n\nConfiguration constants are defined in ServerLogConfigs.java (server-common/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/server/config/ServerLogConfigs.java), which provides LOG_RETENTION_TIME_MILLIS_CONFIG, LOG_RETENTION_TIME_MINUTES_CONFIG, LOG_RETENTION_TIME_HOURS_CONFIG, LOG_RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG, and LOG_CLEANUP_INTERVAL_MS_CONFIG constants.\n\nThe LogManager.scala (core/src/main/scala/kafka/log/LogManager.scala) schedules periodic cleanup using the cleanupLogs() method, which iterates through all logs and calls deleteOldSegments() on each. The scheduler is configured with retentionCheckMs interval (default 5 minutes) to periodically check and delete expired segments.\n\nFor remote storage scenarios, RemoteLogManager.java (storage/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/server/log/remote/storage/RemoteLogManager.java) implements the RemoteLogRetentionHandler inner class with methods isSegmentBreachedByRetentionTime() and isSegmentBreachedByRetentionSize() to check retention breaches for remote segments. The cleanupExpiredRemoteLogSegments() method handles the deletion of remote segments that breach retention policies.\n\nDynamic configuration validation is handled in DynamicBrokerConfig.scala (core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/DynamicBrokerConfig.scala) through validateLogLocalRetentionMs() and validateLogLocalRetentionBytes() methods, which validate remote log manager configuration changes at runtime.\n\nThe topic-level configuration keys are defined in TopicConfig.java (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/config/TopicConfig.java), including RETENTION_MS_CONFIG, RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG, LOCAL_LOG_RETENTION_MS_CONFIG, and LOCAL_LOG_RETENTION_BYTES_CONFIG. RemoteLogManagerConfig.java provides the remote storage-specific retention constants LOG_LOCAL_RETENTION_MS_PROP and LOG_LOCAL_RETENTION_BYTES_PROP."
